"Carrillo P., Delgado-Molina J.A., Medina-Sánchez J.M., Bullejos F.G., Villar-Argaiz M.","Phosphorus inputs unmask negative effects of ultraviolet radiation on algae in a high mountain lake",2008,"Global Change Biology","14","2",,"423","439",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2007.01496.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-53949086439&partnerID=40&md5=1becfca9c4123c5e0e606beaea1fffce","Instituto del Agua, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain; Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain","Carrillo, P., Instituto del Agua, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain, Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain; Delgado-Molina, J.A., Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain; Medina-Sánchez, J.M., Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain; Bullejos, F.G., Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain; Villar-Argaiz, M., Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Granada, 18071 Granada, Spain","Ultraviolet solar radiation (UVR) and atmospheric nutrient loads to pristine ecosystems are global climate change phenomena that simultaneously affect aquatic organisms in ways not easily predicted by single factor studies. Plankton in a high mountain lake was exposed in situ to increasing phosphorus (P) concentrations (mimicking atmospheric pulses) in absence or presence of UVR in order to identify their interactive effect on functional [primary production, organic carbon (C) release (EOC), and percentage of C released (%EOC)], growth rate, structural-physiological (algal biomass, sestonic C, P content, chlorophyll a (Chl a), and Chl a: C ratio, P cell quota, cell-specific Chl a), and stoichiometric (autotroph C: P ratio) traits. The availability of P after the pulse determined the intensity of responses by primary producers to UVR stress. All structural-physiological and functional variables significantly increased by up to two orders of magnitude in response to P enrichment. UV radiation, over a long-term scale, exerted significant deleterious effects on most structural-physiological variables when inorganic P was added at high levels (≥30 μg P L -1). The subsequent unexpected negative synergistic UVR×P effect on algal development did not support our initial hypothesis that P input might buffer the harmful UVR effect. UVR exerted a weak negative effect on primary production but strongly enhanced the absolute and percentage excretion of C (up to 60%), mechanism responsible of a significant reduction in autotroph C: P ratios. We propose that low sestonic C: P ratios are the outcome of an adaptive strategy of algae in environments with high UVR exposure and extreme nutrient limitation and have important implications for C flux through grazing vs. microbial food webs in oligotrophic systems. © 2007 The Authors Journal compilation © 2007 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Extracellular carbon release; High mountain lakes; Primary production; Sestonic C: P ratio; UVR×P interactive effects","alga; carbon flux; climate change; ecosystem function; environmental factor; global change; growth rate; lacustrine environment; mountain region; nutrient availability; nutrient dynamics; nutrient limitation; oligotrophic environment; organic carbon; phosphorus; pristine environment; seston; ultraviolet radiation; algae",,,,,,"(1992) Standard Methods for the Examination of Water and Wastewater, , American Public Health Association APHA, 18th edn. American Public Health Association, Washington; Banaszak, A.T., Photoprotective physiological and biochemical responses of aquatic organisms (2003) Comprehensive Series in Photochemistry and Photobiology, pp. 329-356. , UV Effects in Aquatic Organisms and Ecosystems eds Helbling EW, Zagarese HE, pp, Cambridge Royal Society of Chemistry, Cambridge;